[The mind boggles. To use a Royal Navy phrase, there is clearly a lot of
yard-arm clearing going on here to distance any officials from blame. In
lethal cases of anthrax, diagnosis is quick and straightforward so why the
delay. We had a live animal inspected and now it was inspected post-mortem
after viscera had been inserted into the carcass -- I defy anyone to be
able to do that with a dead cow -- and the vet apparently failed to notice
that the carcass was fevered but the viscera were normal -- if this tale
were true. This Russian (and Soviet) reliance on human vaccination to
protect those in the slaughtering trades indicates the abject failure of
their veterinary programme; if their livestock vaccination & control
procedures worked there is negligible human risk of disease; all modern
countries limit human vaccination, if used, to those in bone meal plants
and wool & hair mills. And there is an apparent demand to vaccinate
shashlyk vendors to protect them in case they are selling infected meat on
the street. I very much doubt that the last outbreak of bovine anthrax in
Krasnodar was as much as 15 years ago. - Mod.MHJ
